				\begin{document}$${(Na,K)}_{Cu}$$\end{document} out-diffuse from the GI, leaving a VCu behind which may either be rinsed away at the surface or occupy a VCu at the GB, leading to a p-type doping at the GI and an n-type doping at the GB. If the grains are columnar, the band bending at the GB induced by the n-type doping would reduce recombination and increase charge collection. Furthermore, the variable chemistry at the GB leads to variable magnitudes of band bending and potential barriers and may help explain the diverse electrical properties exhibited by techniques such as EBIC, KPFM, and CL (see section 4). The benefit of alkali incorporation may be two fold: increase p-type conductivity, and increase band bending at the GB.5(ΝαxCu1−x)(InxGa1−x)Se2bulk0+2VCuGB′+InCuGB°°+2hGB°+2eGB'→Cu(InxGa1−x)Se2bulk0+VCubulk′+hbulk°+NaCuGB°+InCuGB°°+VCuGB′+hGB°+2eGB'\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
